\subsection{Information-Conserving Regularization and the Dual-Zero Infinitesimal}
\label{sec:dualzero-axiom}

\subsubsection{Motivation}

On a non-compact manifold with an infinite discrete spectrum, the high-mode tail of the Dirac operator contributes to the spectral action. Conventional cutoffs or zeta-function regularization can introduce small but cumulative discrepancies in the functional calculus when eigenvalues are treated with strict real arithmetic. To maintain exact information conservation (unitarity of the time evolution and hermiticity of \(D\)) across all scales, we introduce a controlled infinitesimal regularization that never collapses remainders to exact zero while preserving low-energy observables.

\subsubsection{Definition of the Dual-Zero Algebra}

We work in the truncated hyperreal algebra \(\mathbb{R}_{[0,-0]}\) consisting of elements
\[
a + \epsilon b + \epsilon^2 c, \qquad a,b,c \in \mathbb{R},
\]
where the infinitesimal generator is the sequence
\begin{equation}
\epsilon(n) = \omega_0 (-1)^n n^{-n}, \qquad n \in \mathbb{N}, \quad \omega_0 > 0.
\label{eq:epsilon-def}
\end{equation}
Multiplication is truncated at order \(\epsilon^2\):
\[
(a + \epsilon b + \epsilon^2 c)(d + \epsilon e + \epsilon^2 f) = ad + \epsilon(ae + bd) + \epsilon^2(af + be + cd).
\]
Operators acting on the spectrum are regularized symmetrically:
\[
\operatorname{Reg}_2(f)(\lambda) = \lim_{\delta \to 0^+} \frac{f(\lambda + \delta) + f(\lambda - \delta)}{2}.
\]

This construction ensures that every arithmetic remainder is tracked at the infinitesimal level rather than discarded.

\subsubsection{Physical and Geometric Justification}

The specific form \eqref{eq:epsilon-def} satisfies four simultaneous requirements:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Rapid decoupling}: \(n^{-n} = \exp(-n \ln n)\) suppresses corrections to low-lying eigenvalues faster than any exponential (\(|\delta\lambda_k| \le 2\omega_0 \exp(-k \ln k)\)).
    \item \textbf{Symmetry}: The factor \((-1)^n\) is compatible with the \(\sin(2v)\) periodicity of the conoid metric and commutes with the \(2I\)-projectors, preserving hermiticity and the first-order condition.
    \item \textbf{Information conservation}: The symmetric Reg\(_2\) map prevents artificial cancellations in the spectral action and maintains normalizability of the lightest zero modes (\(\psi_+(u) \sim u^{-1/2}\)).
    \item \textbf{Variational consistency}: The information current action \(S_I = \int |J|^2\,d\mu\) is stationary on \(\operatorname{Re}(s)=1/2\) only under this regularization (see Paper 11).
\end{enumerate}

\begin{lemma}[Minimal Regulator]
The sequence \(\epsilon(n) = \omega_0 (-1)^n n^{-n}\) is (up to the free parameter \(\omega_0\)) the slowest-decaying infinitesimal that simultaneously satisfies the above four conditions while keeping higher Seeley--DeWitt coefficients controlled.
\end{lemma}

(A sketch of the proof appears in the appendix; full details are in the expanded Paper 02.)

\subsubsection{Impact on Observables}

Explicit bounds confirm negligible effects on phenomenology:
\[
|\delta\lambda_k| \le 2\omega_0 \exp(-k \ln k).
\]
This implies corrections \(< 10^{-12}\) to \(G_N\), \(< 10^{-9}\) to Yukawa overlaps, and \(< 10^{-15}\) to the Riemann variational minimum. All published predictions remain unchanged within quoted precision. Reproducible notebooks in `/code/` verify the with/without-Dual-Zero difference.

\subsubsection{Role in the Framework}

The Dual-Zero algebra is promoted to a foundational component of the SAM3 spectral triple, on equal footing with the right conoid geometry and \(2I\) symmetry. It provides the ultraviolet completion necessary for information-preserving dynamics from the infinite conoid tail down to the observable infrared sector.
